olonias; the cultural life of the small towns and the cities of San Antonio and Laredo; and the foods, public celebrations, and political attitudes that characterize the region. Arreola's findings thus offer a new appreciation for the great cultural diversity that exists within the Mexican American borderlands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman geographyzMexican-American Border Region. 0aHuman geographyzTexas, South. 0aLandscapesxSocial aspectszTexas, South. 0aMexican AmericanszTexas, SouthxEthnic identity. 0aMexican AmericanszTexas, SouthxHistory. 0aMexican AmericanszTexas, SouthxSocial life and customs. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70510440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292757189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292757189/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK